# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1-4-butanediol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-2-butanediol] This diol was first described by Charles-Adolphe Wurtz in 1859.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-2-butanediol] It is produced industrially by hydration of 1,2-epoxybutane.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-2-butanediol] This process requires a ten- to twenty-fold excess of water to suppress the formation of polyethers.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-2-butanediol] Depending on the amount of excess water, the selectivity varies from 70 to 92%.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-2-butanediol] Sulfuric acid or strongly acidic ion exchange resins may be used as catalysts, which allows the reaction to occur under 160 °C and at slightly above atmospheric pressure.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-2-butanediol] 1,2-Butanediol is a byproduct of the production of 1,4-butanediol from butadiene.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-2-butanediol] It is also a byproduct of the catalytic hydrocracking of starches and sugars such as sorbitol to ethylene glycol and propylene glycol.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-2-butanediol] It can also be obtained from the dihydroxylation of but-1-ene by OsO4.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-2-butanediol] It has been patented for the production of polyester resins and plasticizers.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-2-butanediol] It is a potential feedstock for the industrial production of α-ketobutyric acid, a precursor to some amino acids.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-3-butanediol] 1,3-Butanediol is marketed commercially as an alcohol substitute under the brand name Ketohol.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-3-butanediol] 1,3-Butanediol has sedative, hypotensive and hypoglycaemic action comparable to ethanol, with the (R), also known as (D), enantiomer being more active.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-3-butanediol] Fatty acid esters of 1,3-butanediol such as the acetoacetate, lactate or hexanoate have been studied for inducing ketogenesis.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-3-butanediol] 1,3-Butanediol has been detected in bell peppers (*Capsicum annuum*).
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-3-butanediol] 1,3 Butanediol maintains FDA GRAS status as a flavor molecule.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol-diglycidyl-ether] The IUPAC name is 2-[4-(oxiran-2-ylmethoxy)butoxymethyl]oxirane.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol-diglycidyl-ether] 1,4-Butanediol and epichlorohydrin are reacted in the presence of a Lewis acid as catalyst to form a halohydrin: each hydroxyl group of the diol reacts with an epoxide on epichlorohydrin.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol-diglycidyl-ether] This process is followed by washing with sodium hydroxide to re-form the epoxide rings in dehydrochlorination reaction.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol-diglycidyl-ether] One of the quality control tests would involve measuring the Epoxy value by determination of the epoxy equivalent weight.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol-diglycidyl-ether] A key use is modifying the viscosity and properties of epoxy resins which may then be formulated into CASE applications: Coatings, Adhesives, Sealants, Elastomers, composite materials, fillers, putties, plasters, modelling clay and semiconductors.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol-diglycidyl-ether] It also has a number of medical applications.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol-diglycidyl-ether] The molecule is also used to synthesize other molecules.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol-diglycidyl-ether] As an Epoxy modifier it is classed as an epoxy reactive diluent.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol-diglycidyl-ether] The use of the diluent does effect mechanical properties and microstructure of epoxy resins.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol-diglycidyl-ether] The toxicity is fairly well known and understood and is rated as a severe skin and eye irritant.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] In one industrial chemical synthesis, acetylene reacts with two equivalents of formaldehyde to form butyne-1,4-diol.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] Hydrogenation of butyne-1,4-diol gives butane-1,4-diol.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] It is also made on an industrial scale from maleic anhydride in the Davy process, which is first converted to the methyl maleate ester, then hydrogenated.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] Other routes are from butadiene, allyl acetate and succinic acid.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] A biological route to BD has been commercialized that uses a genetically modified organism.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] The biosynthesis proceeds via 4-hydroxybutyrate.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] Butane-1,4-diol is used industrially as a solvent and in the manufacture of some types of plastics, elastic fibers and polyurethanes.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] In organic chemistry, 1,4-butanediol is used for the synthesis of γ-butyrolactone (GBL).
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] In the presence of phosphoric acid and high temperature, it dehydrates to the important solvent tetrahydrofuran.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] At about 200 °C in the presence of soluble ruthenium catalysts, the diol undergoes dehydrogenation to form butyrolactone.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] It is used to synthesize 1,4-butanediol diglycidyl ether which is then used as a reactive diluent for epoxy resins.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] 1,4-Butanediol is used in the production of polybutylene terephthalate (PBT) plastic.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] World production of butane-1,4-diol was claimed to be about one million metric tons per year and market price is about US$2,000 (€1,600) per ton in 2005.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] In 2013, worldwide production was claimed to be billions of pounds (consistent with approximately one million metric tons).
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] Almost half of it is dehydrated to tetrahydrofuran to make fibers such as Spandex.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] Butane-1,4-diol is also used as a recreational drug known by some users as "Bute", "One Comma Four", "Liquid Fantasy", "One Four Bee" or "One Four B-D-O".
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] Some federal courts in the United States have stated that 1,4-butanediol exerts effects similar to its metabolite, GABA analogue gamma-hydroxybutyrate (GHB), but several other federal courts have ruled that it does not.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] 1,4-but***e***nediol (CAS 110-64-5) may be incorrectly sold as 1,4-butanediol but should not be confused with it.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] Butane-1,4-diol is rapidly converted into GHB acid by the enzymes alcohol dehydrogenase and aldehyde dehydrogenase, and differing levels of these enzymes may account for differences in effects and side effects between users.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] While co-administration of ethanol and GHB already poses serious risks, co-administration of ethanol with 1,4-butanediol will interact considerably and has many other potential risks.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] This is because the same enzymes that are responsible for metabolizing alcohol also metabolize 1,4-butanediol so there is a strong chance of a dangerous drug interaction.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] Butane-1,4-diol seems to have two types of pharmacological actions.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] The major psychoactive effects of 1,4-butanediol are because it is metabolized into GHB; however there is a study suggesting that 1,4-butanediol may have potential alcohol-like pharmacological effects on its own.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] The study arrived at this conclusion based on the finding that butane-1,4-diol coadministered with ethanol led to potentiation of some of the behavioral effects of ethanol.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] However, potentiation of ethanol's effects may simply be caused by competition for the alcohol dehydrogenase and aldehyde dehydrogenase enzymes with co-administered 1,4-butanediol.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] The shared metabolic rate-limiting steps thus leads to slowed metabolism and clearance for both compounds including ethanol's known toxic metabolite acetaldehyde.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] Another study found no effect following intracerebroventricular injection of butane-1,4-diol in rats.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] This contradicts the hypothesis of butane-1,4-diol having inherent alcohol-like pharmacological effects.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] Like gamma-hydroxybutyric acid, butane-1,4-diol is safe only in small amounts.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] Adverse effects in higher doses include nausea, vomiting, dizziness, sedation, vertigo, and potentially death if ingested in large amounts.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] Anxiolytic effects are diminished and side effects increased when used in combination with alcohol.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] While butane-1,4-diol is not currently scheduled federally in the United States, a number of states have classified 1,4-butanediol as a controlled substance.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] Individuals have been prosecuted for possession of 1,4-butanediol under the Federal Analog Act as substantially similar to GHB.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] A federal case in New York in 2002 ruled that 1,4-butanediol could not be considered an analog of GHB under federal law, but that decision was later overturned by the Second Circuit.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] A jury in Federal District Court in Chicago found that 1,4-butanediol was not an analog of GHB under federal law, which was not disputed on the case's appeal to the Seventh Circuit Court of Appeals, however this finding did not affect the outcome of the case.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] In the United Kingdom, 1,4-butanediol was scheduled in December 2009 (along with another GHB precursor, gamma-butyrolactone) as a Class C controlled substance.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] In Germany, the drug is not explicitly illegal, but might also be treated as illegal if used as a drug.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] It is controlled as a Schedule VI precursor in Canada.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] A toy called "Bindeez" ("Aqua Dots" in North America) was recalled by the distributor in November 2007 because of the presence of butane-1,4-diol.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] The toy consists of small beads that stick to each other by sprinkling water.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] The production plant seems to have intended to cut costs by replacing less toxic pentane-1,5-diol with butane-1,4-diol.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] ChemNet China listed the price of butane-1,4-diol at between about US$1,350–2,800 per metric ton, while the price for 1,5-pentanediol is about US$9,700 per metric ton.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] In August 2021, several people fell severely ill after consuming drinks at building L2.01 at the Lichtwiese Campus of Darmstadt Technical University, Germany.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] Seven showed severe symptoms, two were transported to a hospital in Frankfurt am Main, and a 30-year-old person was, for a time, in a critical state.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] Butane-1,4-diol had been detected in milk packages, as well as in water filters.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] At the location, detectives also found bromophenols and dicyclohexylamine.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] A variety of 1,4-butanediol derivatives are GHB-like drugs or GHB receptor agonists.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] These include GHB itself, γ-butyrolactone (GBL), aceburic acid, ethyl acetoxy butanoate (EAB), Γ-crotonolactone, γ-hydroxybutyraldehyde, γ-hydroxyvaleric acid (GHV), γ-valerolactone (GVL), γ-hydroxycrotonic acid (GHC or T-HCA), and 4-hydroxy-4-methylpentanoic acid (UMB68), among others.
[src:1-4-butanediol/1-4-butanediol] An analogue that is not a 1,4-butanediol derivative but is related and still shows affinity for the GHB receptor is 3-chloropropanoic acid (UMB66).
[src:1-4-butanediol/11-ketoprogesterone] 11-Ketoprogesterone is reportedly devoid of androgenic, estrogenic, and progestogenic activity.
[src:1-4-butanediol/11-ketoprogesterone] 11β-Hydroxyprogesterone has also been reported to be devoid of progestogenic activity, but has subsequently been reported to possess about 1% of the progestogenic activity of progesterone.
[src:1-4-butanediol/11-ketoprogesterone] A halogenated derivative of 11-ketoprogesterone, 9α-bromo-11-ketoprogesterone, possesses relatively high progestogenic activity.
[src:1-4-butanediol/11-ketoprogesterone] Similarly to 11α-hydroxyprogesterone and 11β-hydroxyprogesterone, 11-ketoprogesterone is reported to act as an inhibitor of the enzyme 11β-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase.
[src:1-4-butanediol/11-ketoprogesterone] It has also been found to act as a weak negative allosteric modulator of the GABAA receptor.
[src:1-4-butanediol/2-2-2-trichloroethanol] The pharmacological effects of this compound in humans are similar to those of its prodrug chloral hydrate, and of chlorobutanol.
[src:1-4-butanediol/2-2-2-trichloroethanol] Historically, it has been used as a sedative hypnotic.
[src:1-4-butanediol/2-2-2-trichloroethanol] The hypnotic drug triclofos (2,2,2-trichloroethyl phosphate) is metabolized *in vivo* to 2,2,2-trichloroethanol.
[src:1-4-butanediol/2-2-2-trichloroethanol] Chronic exposure may result in kidney and liver damage.
[src:1-4-butanediol/2-2-2-trichloroethanol] 2,2,2-Trichloroethanol can be added to SDS-PAGE gels in order to enable fluorescent detection of proteins without a staining step, for immunoblotting or other analysis methods.
[src:1-4-butanediol/2-2-2-trichloroethanol] 2,2,2-Trichloroethanol is an effective protecting group for carboxylic acids due to its ease in addition and removal.
[src:1-4-butanediol/2-2-diethyl-1-3-propanediol] Treatment of the aldehyde 2-ethylbutyraldehyde with formaldehyde and potassium hydroxide gives a crossed Cannizzaro reaction yielding prenderol.
[src:1-4-butanediol/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] Diberal, unlike most barbiturates, can have convulsant actions.
[src:1-4-butanediol/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] This is uncommon, as barbiturates typically enhance the function of GABA as allorestic modulators and agonists (at higher doses), therefore having anticonvulsant properties.
[src:1-4-butanediol/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] Depending on which isomer is used, it can have either convulsant or anticonvulsant actions.
[src:1-4-butanediol/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] The different pharmacological profile between isomers is thought to be due to the differences in the formation of hydrogen bonds at the binding sites.
[src:1-4-butanediol/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] (+)-DMBB is the atypical enantiomer of diberal.
[src:1-4-butanediol/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] It is atypical in the means that it has convulsant action, unlike most barbiturate drugs.
[src:1-4-butanediol/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] Unlike (+)-DMBB, the (−)-isomer is similar to most barbiturates by having anticonvulsant action.
[src:1-4-butanediol/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] It has been found that administration of (−)-DMBB reverses the convulsant actions of (+)-DMBB.
[src:1-4-butanediol/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] (−)-DMBB is slightly more potent than pentobarbital in its depressant properties.
